<br>
Unless you have personal experience with both drugs, you have no frame of reference and no way to quantify such a ridiculous statement.  Yes, both induce &quot;a state of euphoria.&quot;  Tryng to define &quot;euphoria&quot; is like trying to guess how many cups of water are in the Mississippi.  I've experience a pot high and an opium high, and let me tell you, the difference in scale and effect are monumental.<br>
<br>
Similarly, by your reasoning, I could go to microfiche and dig up every capital crime in which the perpetrator was a tobacco smoker, and then make a case for tobacco inducing &quot;irrational&quot; behavior.  Irrational people are irrational; people with slow reflexes have slow reflexes...marijuana simply accentuates characteristics.  Sure, lots of rapists, murderers, and everyday common criminals have traces of THC in their bloodstream.  A lot of them also have brown hair, yet brown hair is still legal.  Strangely enough, a lot of great cultural icons, artists, and yes, even statesmen have traces of THC in their bloodstream also.  Weird, huh?  Hell, let's just grab some facts out of the air and make a random correlation now and then claim it's been &quot;proven.&quot;<br>
<br>
